		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Making it mobile friendly, hmm... Doesn't it require to update the content so it works better on mobile?</div><br />I assume the MobileFrontend extension will handle most of the changes, except for wide tables as used in pages such as <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Mapper" class="postlink">Mapper</a>.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I have no idea what is the obsession people have with mobile this mobile that. Sometime it worth it, in other case it doesn't.  Do you make nes app on your phone?</div><br />Tablet with clip-on, Bluetooth, or USB OTG keyboard, presumably. After <a href="https://hardware.slashdot.org/story/12/12/31/1829212/does-2012-mark-the-end-of-the-netbook" class="postlink">10 inch laptops got discontinued at the end of 2012</a>, some people have ported <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=132765#p132765" class="postlink">ASM6</a> and <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=140283#p140283" class="postlink">ca65</a> to Android for use on a tablet as a workaround for having to replace a laptop with a tablet. My six-year-old 10 inch Dell still runs, but not everyone is as fortunate as I.<br /><br />A 9-10 inch tablet shares some attributes with phones, such as the imprecise pointing device. But it shares other attributes with laptops, such as not needing to zoom in nearly as often. Despite this, Google presents search results as if tablets were phones.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
